{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600684/1930052601/0014.xml":{"full_text":"TICKER CLUB LIST\nWILL BE PREPARED\n\u2022S\u2019\nGovernors of New Broker Or\nganization to Hold Meet\ning Tomorrow.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nAs the Anal step the\norganization of the Ticker Club of\nWashington, the board of governors will\nmeet tomorrow afternoon and decide\nj\nLouts E. Purnell.\nwhat members shall\nbe the official rep\nresentatives of the\n16 firms now com\nposing the club.\nThe different brok\nerage houses have\nIndicated to the\ngovernors the per\nsons they wish to\nrepresent them In\nthe club, and these\nare the names\nwhich will be acted\nupon at tomorrow\u2019s\nmeeting. The in\ndications are that\nthe club will start\nout with about 40\nof the leading\nbrokers in the city\non the roster as representatives of the\ndifferent firms.\nMembership is open to partners, man\nagers and assistant managers of the\nconcerns doing a New York Stock Ex\nchange business. In some instances\nas many as three members of the same\nfirm have asked to go down on the list\nas representatives. The chief aim of\nthe new club is mutual protection, and\nthe interest displayed in the organiza\ntion has been almost surprising to those\nassuming the burden of getting the as\nsociation on a solid basis.\nThe officers of the Ticker Club are:\nOeorge A. Garrett of F. B. Keech St Co.,\n{resident; A. Chester Flather. G. M. P.\nlurphv Co., vice president, and\nArthur' Foraker, Eastman, Dillon Co.,\nsecretary-treasurer.\nPurnell Wins Essay Honor*.\nLouis E. Purnell, who won second\nprise In the institute's essay contest and\ngets a trip to the District Bankers\u2019 As\nsociation annual convention at Ashe\nville, N. C., Is employed as a book\nkeeper In the Park Road branch of the\nRiggs National Bank, of which Carl H.\nDonch is manager.\nThe easay winner is not quite 21 years\nof age. He was born in Baltimore and\ngot his early education in Pittsburgh\nand Cleveland. After coming to Wash\nington he graduated from Eastern High\nSchool.\nHe Is taking courses in Washington\nChapter. American Institute of Bank\ning. and is a favorite among his asso\nciates. this being shown by the fact\nthat he is assistant superintendent of\nthe Ingraham Memorial Sunday School.\nThe young man has been with the Riggs\nBank about two years, being transferred\nseveral months ago from the North\nwest Branch to the Park Road Branch.\nShip Contracts Involve $21,000,008.\nMuch local interest is noted in the\nAnnouncement that Paul W. Chapman,\npresident of United States Lines, has\nsigned a contract with New York Ship\nbuilding Co., a subsidiary of American\nBrown Boveri Electric Corporation, for\nthe construction of two first-class liners\nof 30.000 gross tons each. These ves\nsels. the total cost of which will run\nover $21,000,000, will be the largest and\nfinest ships ever built in this country.\nContract calls for completion of the first\nship within 26 months, or July, 1932\nand for the second ship within 30\nmonths, or November, 1932.\nNew ships will be similar in exterior\ndesign to the Leviathan, except that\nthev will have two funnels, while the\nLeviathan has three. They will have a\nlength of 705 feet and a beam of 86\nfeet and will carry first, tourist and\nthird-class passengers to a capacity of\nAbout 1,300.\nAbout 250 Convention Reservations.\nClaude H. Woodward, chairman of\nthe transportation committee for the\nannual convention of the District\nBankers\u2019 Association, reports that re\nquests for accommodations for about\n250 people have already been received.\nThis means the largest attendance on\nrecord.\nIt is stated that no reservations will\nbe handled after Saturday. May 31. At\nthe present rate the \"standing room\nonly\u201d sign will be out before that time.\nThe work of all the committee* has been\ncompleted and the program turned over\nto the association president, W. J. Wal\nler, for submission to the printer.\nThe last \"call\u201d Just sent out notified\nthe delegates and their friends that the\ntwo special trains will leave the Union\nStation on Wednesday evening, June 4,\nAt 6 o'clock.\nTraction is Market Feature.\nCapital Traction stock was the fea\nture of the Washington stock market\nwhen trading was resumed today. Tire\nstock opened with three shares selling\nat 70. Then followed seven sales in\nvolving 120 shares at 69%. The market\nclosed with a tiny sale of two shares,\nselling at a new low mark on\nthis move.\nFederal-American Co. common regis\ntered six sales of 10 shares each at 31,\nPotomac Electric Power s\\' 2 P er cent\npreferred came out at 107 and 20 shares\nof Carpel Corporation changed hands\nAt 26 3 4. Washington Railway Si Elec\ntric preferred again sold at 98'/ 2\nBonds were very quiet. Washington\nGas 5s sold at 103\u2018a and Georgetown\nGas 5s at 102. The exchange will be\nclosed two days this week, Friday, Me\nmorial day, and Saturday.\nMeehan Firm Here One Year.\nToday marks the first anniversary of\nthe opening of the Washington office\nof M. J. Meehan Sc Co., members of\nthe New York Stock Exchange, who.\none year ago. established their local\nbranch on the ground floor of the Wash\nington Hotel, with Frank J. F. Thiel,\nresident partner, in charge. Mr. Thlei\nfor many years occupied the position of\nAssistant Treasurer of the United I\nStates.\nSince opening the Washington of-1\nflee the Meehan firm, which is one of i\nthe largest on the New York exchange.\nhas opened two offices In Detroit and i\nsuccessfully initiat'd the innovation of!\nestablishing branch brokerage offices on\ntransatlantic liners, now operating reg- I\nular brokerage service on the Leviathan, j\nthe B'rengaria and the Bremen.\nNotes in Financial District.\nJ. Thilman Hendrick, chairman of\nth\u00bb board of directors of the Lanston\nMonotype Ce., has returned \u00bbo Wash\nington after a short business trip to\nthe London office. He was accom\npanied by the president, Harvey D.\nBest.\nThe desk of Robert N. Harper, presi\ndes' of the District National Bank, is I\nAt\u2019 buried with flowers sent him in\ner \u2019tion with nls retiring as head i\no bank and election as chairman\nOs e board.\nJohn E Parker of G. M. P. Murphy\nCo. has returned to the H street cf- j\nflee after several days passed at Vir\nginia Beach.\nAn increase of 11. l per cent in total\nbuilding operations in April, as com\npared with March, is reported by the\nDepartment of Labor. The report is\nbased on figures received from 285 cities\nwith a population of more than 25,000\npersons.\nAlthough some branches of lndustrv\nand trade have shown slight increase!-\nIn activity in th\u00bb last few weeks, definit\nsigns of business revival are still absem\nGuaranty Trust Co. of New York sav\nIn the current issue of the Guarant-\nSurvey.\nR. W. McNeel, Boston economist, say I\nthat \"the stock market is grounding oi\nbottom. The worst of the business d r\nprasaion is over. The definite prospect\nIs for improvement in business in the\ncoming months.\u201d\npina n\u2019 i a\nI NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE I\nReceived hv Prlr- wire Direct to The Star CHBee.\nNotice\u2014All stocks are sold In one hundred-share lots\nexcepting those designated by the letter a (Sts) (285)\nwhich shows those stocks to be eold In odd lota only.\n\u2014Pryy 1030 Stock and Said Free\nHigh Low Dividend Rate Add 00. Hieh. low Otoe* Close\n87V, 28% Adams Exp 11.001... 82 32% 31 Sl** 30%\n150** llh Air Reduction 13)... 27 145% 144 145 MS'*\n86 21 Air Way T1 Apt* 14). 2 25% 25% 25% 22%\n2% 1% Ajax Rubber 6 1% 1% 1% 1%\n9% 6% Alaska Juneau 12 6*\u00ab 6% 6% 6%\n15% 8% Albany Wrap Paper. 2 10% 10% 10% 11\n35% 23 Allegheny C<Rp 164 28% 27% 27% 27%\n107% 96% Alleg Cp w S3O w 5% 2 101 100%. 101 100',\n96% 89% AllegCp x S3O w 5%. 2 93% 93% 93% 98%\n99% 95 Alleg Cp w *4O w 5%. 2 95% 95 95 96%\nI 843 265% Allied Ch A Dv*in6) 32 316 308 309% 306\n1 68 49% Allla-Chalmere 13).. 53 64% 63 63 63%\ni 29% 18 Amerada Corp 2 26% 26% 26% 2